comments.body:
The cleanest data model is: **the grant request is saved in the GitHub thread as an agent-owned hidden marker**, the same way pending implementation approvals are stored today.

Existing precedent:

- Pending approvals are encoded as `<!-- sepo-agent-request base64:... -->` in an issue/discussion comment.
- The payload is base64url JSON.
- The resolver later scans comments, finds the marker by `request_id`, checks it is not already satisfied, and dispatches from that embedded metadata.
- See [`approval.ts`](https://github.com/self-evolving/repo/blob/main/.agent/src/approval.ts) and [`prepare-approval.ts`](https://github.com/self-evolving/repo/blob/main/.agent/src/cli/prepare-approval.ts).

For external-user grants, I’d use the same storage model with a new marker type:

```md
@external-user does not currently have access to run `/answer`.

A maintainer can grant this request once with:

```text
@sepo-agent /grant grant-abc123
```

<!-- sepo-agent-grant-request base64:... -->
```

Decoded payload shape:

```ts
interface GrantRequest {
  kind: "grant_request";
  schema_version: 1;

  grant_id: string;              // "grant-abc123"
  status: "pending";             // consumed by editing marker/comment later

  route: "answer" | "implement" | "review" | "fix-pr" | "create-action";
  requested_skill?: string;

  requester_login: string;
  requester_association: string; // NONE, FIRST_TIMER, etc.
  request_text: string;

  source_kind: "issue_comment" | "discussion_comment" | "review_comment" | "issue_body";
  source_comment_id?: string;
  source_comment_url?: string;

  target_kind: "issue" | "pull_request" | "discussion";
  target_number: number;
  target_url: string;

  created_at: string;
  expires_at: string;

  allowed_grantor_associations: ["OWNER", "MEMBER", "COLLABORATOR"];
}
```

When a maintainer replies:

```text
@sepo-agent /grant grant-abc123
```

the grant workflow would:

1. Scan the issue/discussion comments for `sepo-agent-grant-request`.
2. Decode the marker and find `grant_id`.
3. Verify it is unexpired and not already consumed.
4. Verify the commenter is allowed to grant, probably `OWNER`, `MEMBER`, or `COLLABORATOR`.
5. Dispatch the original request using the saved `route`, `request_text`, `target_*`, and `requester_login`.
6. Edit the grant-request comment to add a visible audit row and hidden consumed marker:

```md
| Granted by | Granted to | Route | Run |
|---|---|---|---|
| @maintainer | @external-user | `answer` | ... |

<!-- sepo-agent-grant-consumed -->
```

So there is no new database for the one-shot UX. The GitHub comment is the source of truth, just like existing approval requests. That keeps it auditable, local to the thread, and compatible with the current workflow style.

I would only add a separate durable store later for **standing grants**, for example “allow @user to use `/answer` for 30 days.” That would need a different model, probably a repo-owned config file or protected branch state. For this issue, the one-shot grant marker is enough and safer.
